{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7ab21551-bffe-4f0c-b490-9037b7d35382","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these places:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` or `.crash` files:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for the same files with a GUI.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — macOS disables them by default. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file typically lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`log show`** — Check the unified system log for crash details:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'eventMessage contains \"your_app_name\"' --last 1h\n   ```\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is usually the quickest path — it includes the faulting thread, stack trace, and signal info without any prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"22f6cff2-ced9-46c5-8bfb-11e19a877931","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":320,"requestId":"1BC1:9309E:DB6FC7:FAD328:6A028691"},"id":"63080355-20b1-4b9c-8c1e-027601fb5eb6","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:47:06.695Z","parentId":"6480f860-a1e2-47da-9f84-0be37cccfd53"}
